Morpheus API Open Actions:

Key Categories:

1) Private Key Auth  
2) User Flow (Frontend)  
3) Sexy Swagger  
4) Automation  
5) Productionalization

Private Key Auth  
There will be multiple users using this API gateway, each having their own private keys. Currently, the proxy router functions as a single user solution, with a single private key in the env file. Whichever solution we choose to implement must take this into consideration.

1) The simplest, and worst option, is to maintain a database with user email and private key. Whenever there is an API call to the API Gateway, the gateway will pull the private key, transfer it to the proxy router and store as the private key env variable, and execute the transaction. This puts a tremendous amount of risk on our plate, having to manage user private keys in our own database, and passing them from the Gateway to the Proxy Router.   
2) A slightly better option would be to similarly maintain this database using a key management service. This removes the risk of managing the keys directly ourselves, but still contains risks with passing those to the proxy router.  
3) The best option, although the most difficult to implement is a delegation service. The delegation service would allow a user to delegate certain functionality, like “sending tokens” to the compute router. This could be done without ever sharing a private key. We need to further evaluate the feasibility of this and if it is possible within the current proxy router configurations. 

We need to maintain a connection between user account, API key, and ability to transact on their behalf. A single user will have multiple API keys. Each API key will have a maximum of 1 session key associated to it, if they have an open session. 

User Flow (Frontend)  
We need to develop a front-end to the website with basic user account settings. Although some users will choose to do this through the API, the majority of users will setup their account through a UI. If we choose option C above, this may become a hard requirement rather than a soft one. The front-end UI account settings must allow for users to create their account, get their auth keys, and manage their API keys. This is where they would also setup any automation configurations. Additionally, to be more professional, we would need some sort of homepage and basic website with information on the product and morpheus. 

Sexy Swagger  
The swagger UI is currently the default fastAPI swagger, which is functional but plain and messy. Users have become more accustomed to well-designed API reference pages and API playgrounds (ref: Venice [https://docs.venice.ai/api-reference/endpoint/chat/completions](https://docs.venice.ai/api-reference/endpoint/chat/completions))

This provides a couple key value propositions for the user:

1) Information. The Venice api UI, (potentially using zod? for info) explains each of the endpoints and the relevant information about how they work and what each setting does.   
2) Usability. Within the Venice API playground it further defines required vs optional fields with dropdowns for pre-selection where applicable. You are more likely to produce a compliant API call when you know what you can vs must include, and the criteria around providing it.  
3) Automation. The Venice API playground has input boxes and a final cURL (and others) output box. The information that you include in the fields populates into the output box, which you can choose to either execute or copy and paste into your terminal or code. It also provides sample requests and responses to get a better idea of a “normal” call  
4) Code Support. Most of these API playgrounds include various code generation options like what I mentioned with cURL. You can simply click “Python” “Javascript” “PHP” “Go” or “Java” to see what code should be used to facilitate the request based on your inputs.

Automation  
The end goal user-flow for this product is the following: 1\) Create Account, 2\) Create API Key 3\) Approve Funds (whether through private key, or delegation), 4\) Send request with API base URL and API Key. 

Users don’t want to manage sessions. They don’t want to find models, or providers, or bids. We need to implement a solution where a request to /chat/completions initiates a script that A) Approves Funds for Spending, B) Identifies a model ID based on their model input. I.e. They may say Llama 3.3 or o1-mini. We need to directly choose that model from the /models list, or facilitate the call through routing and/or standard tags. C) Initiate a session based on the model ID selected, and D) forward the prompt to the proxy router with the above information included. If the user already has a session open, the API key they use already pulls the session ID from the database. 

The user must have the ability to choose whether or not they want session rollover (i.e. when session ends, start a new one). They also should choose if/when a session is closed. We need to decide if we want to close on inactivity or close after a standard period of time. This similarly will help define the session length selected within the automation. 

Productionalization  
The final step is getting this thing live. We need to conduct a comprehensive review of the codebase and run our own audit to make sure that data and funds remain private, and that we have limited edge cases. Following our audit, we need to determine the right way to host this in production, and manage our own internal API and Auth Keys. We should create a budget for this and understand our monthly costs.
